{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01N9i5jW1giLjhneiNbgouUE","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now I have all 386 vendors with their spend amounts. I need to classify each one with a category and department. Let me go through them systematically.\n\nLet me classify each vendor:\n\n1. (Blank) - $137.30 - Unknown/Other → G&A\n2. 4I Advisory Services - $71,860 - Professional Services/Consulting → Professional Services\n3. 4I Management Consulting Private Limited - $12,117 - Management Consulting → Professional Services\n4. 4Imprint Direct Ltd - $2,436 - Promotional Products → Marketing\n5. 6Sense Insights Inc - $75.56 - Marketing Intelligence/ABM → Marketing\n\n\n6. Acclime Corporate Services - $5,413 - Corporate Services/Compliance → G&A\n7. Acclime Usa, Inc - $4,995 - Corporate Services/Compliance → G&A\n8. Accutrainee Limited - $38,841 - Training/Learning → G&A\n9. Adamma Info Services Private Limited - $273 - IT Services → Engineering\n10. Adobe Systems Software - $3,929 - Creative Software → Marketing\n11. Advena - $153.89 - Unknown → G&A\n12. Aetna Life And Casualty Ltd - $124,661 - Health Insurance → G&A\n13. Ag Grid Ltd - $2,653 - Data Grid/Developer Tools → Engineering\n14. Agram Life Osiguranje D.O.O. - $24,952 - Life Insurance → G&A\n15. Aha! Labs Inc - $3,689 - Product Roadmap/Developer Tools → Product\n16. Akton D.O.O. - $3,254 - Unknown Croatian company → G&A\n17. Allianz Australia Workers' Compensation (Victoria) Limited - $6,099 - Workers Compensation Insurance → G&A\n18. Allianz Wa - $971 - Insurance → G&A\n19. Amazon (Aus) - $233 - E-commerce/Marketplace → G&A\n20. Amazon Web Services Inc. - $5,153 - Cloud Services → Engineering\n\nContinuing through the vendor list, I'm categorizing each expense by vendor type and assigning them to the appropriate cost center, with most falling into G&A while specialized services like development tools and cloud infrastructure route to Engineering or Product. Continuing through the vendor list, I'm seeing more software and service providers—Ariba for procurement, Atlassian for development tools, Australian Payroll for HR services, and various smaller vendors for communications, food, and office supplies, each categorized by their primary function. Continuing through the vendor list, I'm seeing more service providers across different categories—share registry and business consulting services, legal firms, event management, telecommunications, and various other operational vendors, each mapped to their appropriate cost centers. Continuing through the vendor list, I'm seeing more catering and facilities expenses, along with insurance providers and professional services being categorized into their respective cost centers. Continuing through the vendor list, categorizing co-working spaces, share registries, design firms, and various other service providers into their appropriate expense categories like Facilities, Finance, and Product. Continuing through the expense list, I'm seeing more vendor entries with their costs and categorizations - companies like Docusign for e-signature services, logistics providers, business intelligence tools, and various consulting firms, each mapped to their appropriate expense categories. Continuing through the vendor list with more service providers and their allocations across departments. Continuing through the expense list, I'm seeing more vendor categorizations including restaurant services, individual contractors, domain hosting, consulting fees, parking facilities, gaming platforms, and major cloud/advertising spend from Google at nearly $25K, along with courier and remote access tools. Continuing through the expense list, I'm seeing more vendor entries with their amounts and categorizations—hotels, utilities, restaurants, and various service providers being sorted into expense categories like G&A, Facilities, and M&A. Continuing through the vendor list with more expense categories and allocations. Continuing through the vendor list, I'm seeing more service categories being mapped to their cost centers—corporate secretarial services going to Legal, insurance brokers and individual contractors to G&A, real estate and facilities management to Facilities, along with various smaller expenses for print services and food vendors. Continuing through the vendor list, categorizing each entry by department and expense type. Continuing through the expense list with more vendor entries—hotel accommodations, IT recruiting services, accounting support, media promotion, HR consulting, and various other operational expenses across different departments. Continuing through the vendor list, I'm seeing more travel and business service providers. Navan appears twice with significant expenses around $358k and $58k for travel management, while other entries like NCC Services and New Star Networks are smaller IT-related vendors in the engineering category.\n\nNow moving into the N-O section, I'm cataloging cosmetics retailers, legal services, food establishments, and facilities-related vendors like office relocation and catering services, with amounts ranging from under $500 to several thousand dollars. Continuing through the vendor list, I'm seeing more entries with their amounts and categorizations—various services like log management software, shipping providers, HR tools, and local businesses getting sorted into their respective expense categories. Continuing through the expense categorization list, I'm now working through entries in the P section, assigning vendors like employee benefits providers, project management organizations, event venues, tax advisors, and hospitality services to their appropriate departments like G&A, Finance, Marketing, and Facilities. Continuing through the vendor list, I'm seeing more entries with telecom expenses, banking services, and various Croatian service providers mixed in with gifts, data services, and event planning vendors. Continuing through the vendor list with IT services, communication platforms, and various operational expenses—Slack for team collaboration, Smartsheet for project management, and several other service providers categorized across engineering, professional services, and general administration. Continuing through the vendor list, I'm seeing more departmental allocations—sports associations and student services going to G&A, a major M&A platform expense of nearly $40K, telecommunications and moving services distributed across various cost centers, and a student catering facility running about $8,200. Continuing through the vendor list, I'm seeing more service providers and telecom companies - IT recruitment firms, telecommunications vendors like Telefónica and Telemach, event organizers, catering services, and transport-related expenses all being categorized into their respective cost centers. Continuing through the expense list, I'm seeing more vendor categorizations including a significant Tm Forum charge of $57,560, various telecom and service providers, office space costs, and project management tools, all being sorted into their respective departments. Continuing through the expense list, I'm seeing more vendor categorizations—healthcare services, investment firms, IT consulting, visa services, printing supplies, wellness programs, telecommunications, and more entries being processed into their respective cost categories. Continuing through the vendor list, I'm seeing the tail end of entries with Yellow Submarine and various other companies—Croatian utilities, office spaces, workflow automation tools, and a law firm rounding out the dataset.\n\nNow I'm refining some of the categorizations where the spend amounts or vendor types warrant a closer look. Cloudcrossing and Cloud Technology Solutions are both Google Cloud resellers, so those belong in Engineering under cloud infrastructure. Telefonica Global Services is a significant telecom expense, but I'm keeping it in G&A since it's connectivity-related rather than core engineering. Weking is a substantial Croatian IT outsourcing vendor that should go to Engineering, and Tmforum as a telecom industry association fits better in G&A. Innovent Spaces is another office space vendor for Facilities, and I'm still working through the remaining entries.\n\nFor the office space vendors—Space & Co, The Office Group, and Zagreb Tower—those are all clearly Facilities expenses. On HubSpot, since the vendor name doesn't specify which product, I'm defaulting to the CRM categorization under Sales. Google Ireland Limited is trickier at $24,798—it could be either Google Ads for Marketing or Google Workspace for G&A, and I need to make a judgment call based on the amount and context. Now I'm categorizing the remaining vendors: Performancepro is performance management software for HR, Kimble Applications is a PSA tool used by professional services firms, and Planful is a financial planning platform that belongs in Finance. I need to make sure I'm using the exact vendor names from the spreadsheet, including any special characters that were flagged during extraction.\n\nGenerating classification table...","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":10204,"cache_read_input_tokens":16571,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":10204,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0},"output_tokens":8,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"df4aae7e-bdba-470a-b08e-3af9b2992d6c","uuid":"1eefcf65-d581-4373-9316-eda5609bfa2a"}
